Note that problem $\mathcal{P}^b_k$ is non-convex being the ratio of two convex functions.
Recently several algorithms \cite{Malik2000}, \cite{Bresson2010}, \cite{Hein2010}, \cite{Hein2011}, have been proposed to minimize relaxations of the balanced cut problem that are similar to
(\ref{bal_cheeger}). Typically these algorithms give excellent numerical performance, although theoretical convergence proofs have not been provided yet. In \cite{Bresson2012}, it has been proposed a first algorithm minimizing (\ref{exact_rel}) along with a  proof of  convergence to
a critical point of the original problem.
The proposed algorithm  based on an explicit-implicit gradient method  is described in Algorithm
\ref{algorithm:Alg_balanced}.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\small
\quad {For} $k=2,\ldots,N$\smallskip

\quad \quad \text{Set} $n=0$, ${\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^n={\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}^0$  nonzero vector with $\text{m}({\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^n)=0$;

\quad \quad \quad\quad $\beta>0$, $0< \epsilon\ll 1$;

\quad \quad {Repeat}

\quad \quad \quad   ${\mbox{\boldmath $w$}}^n \in \text{sign}({\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^n)$,

\quad \quad \quad     ${\mbox{\boldmath $h$}}^n={\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^n+\beta {\mbox{\boldmath $v$}}^n$,

\quad \quad \quad       $\hat{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}}_k^n=\underset{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k \in \mathcal{X}^b_k}{\arg \min} \;\text{TV}_{+}({\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k)+{\displaystyle} \frac{\text{E}({\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^n)}{2 \beta}{\parallel {\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k-{\mbox{\boldmath $h$}}^n  \parallel}_2^2 $, \smallskip

\quad \quad \quad          $\hat{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}}_k^n=\hat{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}}_k^n-\text{m}(\hat{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}}_k^n)\mathbf{1}$

\quad \quad \quad          ${\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^{n+1}={\displaystyle} \frac{\hat{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}}_k^n}{{\parallel \hat{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}}_k^n  \parallel}_2 }$, $n=n+1$

    \quad \quad {until} $\mid\text{E}({\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^n)-\text{E}({\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k^{n-1})\mid <\epsilon$

\quad {end}
       \caption{: Balanced Total Variation}
 \label{algorithm:Alg_balanced}

\end{algorithm}\vspace{-0.1cm}


\section{Numerical results}
In this section we assess the effectiveness of the proposed
methods  through simulation results.
As an example to test the efficiency of the method based on the unbalanced total variation minimization, we plot
in Fig. \ref{fig:fig1}   the optimal basis vectors $\{{\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_k\}_{k=2}^{7}$, obtained  by running Algorithm  \ref{algorithm:Alg_unbalanced}
 for a directed graph composed of $N=20$ nodes (the intensity of the vector entries is encoded in the color associated to each vertex).
It can be noted that the optimal basis  favors the appearance of clusters.
Furthermore, the value assumed by the basis vectors within each cluster is exactly constant. This is in contrast with the Laplacian method
where the eigenvectors of ${\mbox{\boldmath $L$}}$ are only slowly varying within the clusters, but not exactly constant.
This implies, for example, that in our case no further thresholding steps are needed to obtain the final cluster configuration.

From Fig.\ref{fig:fig1} we can also observe that some clusters are composed of isolated nodes. To deter such solutions, in Fig. \ref{fig:fig2} we report  the optimal basis vectors found by minimizing the balanced cut through Algorithm \ref{algorithm:Alg_balanced}.
For some bases, e.g.  ${\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_5$, ${\mbox{\boldmath $x$}}_6$, it can be observed a more balanced partition as compared to  the unbalanced optimization.

